Data Dictionary:¶

(https://developer.datafiniti.co/docs/product-data-schema)

id: The ASIN (Amazon identifier) used for this product.
dateAdded: The date this product was first added to the product database.
DateUpdated: The most recent date this product was updated or seen by our system.
name: The product's name
asins: The ASIN (Amazon identifier) used for this product.
brand: The brand name of this product.
categories: A list of category keywords used for this product across multiple sources.
primaryCategories: A list of standardized categories to which this product belongs.
keys: A list of internal Datafiniti identifiers for this product.
manufacturer: The manufacturer of this product.
manfacturerNumber: The manufacturer or model number of this product.
reviews.date: The date the review was posted.
reviews.dateSeen: The date when the review was seen by Datafiniti.
reviews.numHelpful: The number of people that found this review helpful.
reviews.rating: A 1 to 5 start value for the review.
reviews.sourceURLs: A list of URLs where this review was seen.
reviews.text: The full (or available) text of the review.
reviews.title: The review's title.
reviews.username: The reviewer's username.

Based on the Data Dictionary, it looks like I can already drop a few columns.
These are:

dateAdded
DateUpdated
keys
reviews.dateSeen
reviews.sourceURLs
manufacturerNumber

These columns are used for the aggregators internal organization and don't reflect on the interaction between a consumer and Amazon, or they duplicate data found in other columns.

Other columns that I might consider dropping after further exploration:
categories: full of every category tag for a product, it'll probably be much less useful than 'primaryCategories'.
reviews.title: currently unclear whether or not this contain more/less value than the review body.

Also worth noting when I check for duplicate values, I'm probably not going to see any duplicates if I use each row as a unique key. I might have to consider only a few columns to check for duplicate values.

Duplicate Values Check¶

Checking for duplicates is a bit tricky as we'll probably see duplicate phrases in reviews like: 'works well', 'ok', etc. This is still data I want to keep; it doesn't provide concrete proof of faulty data. It's simply phrases that many different reviews used.

I'm first checking duplicates using the entire row of columns as a unique key

In [10]:
df.duplicated(keep=False).sum()
Out[10]:
0

That didn't turn up any duplicates but I'm going to broaden my criteria a bit to see what I can find.

I'm choosing several columns to open up the search. These are: id, reviews.date, reviews.text, reviews.username.
If you look back at the data dictionary for a description of each of these, I believe that combining them creates a fairly accurate unique key to identify legitimate faulty data.

Adding classification target¶

Create new column 'sent_label'. Reviews with starts 1-3 will be given a value of 0 (negative), while 4-5 will be given a value of 1 (positive).

In [32]:
# glance
print(df['reviews.rating'].value_counts())

5    19869
4     5637
3     1199
1      965
2      616
Name: reviews.rating, dtype: int64

Clearly we're going to have a huge class imbalance using really any critieria. Even if we only chose 5 stars as a positive review, and considered everything else negative, we'd still have to deal with a class imbalance.

In [33]:
condition = [(df['reviews.rating'] <= 3), (df['reviews.rating'] >= 4)]
values = [0,1]

df['sent_label'] = np.select(condition, values)
In [34]:
print(df['sent_label'].value_counts())

1    25506
0     2780
Name: sent_label, dtype: int64

Theres the huge class imbalance. Almost a 1 to 10 imbalance shown. We can takes steps to mitigate this using sklearn options in the appropriate classifiers.

In [35]:
del(condition, values)

Its unlikely that we'll get more information about product sentiment by removing words to be run through our models.

def lemmatize_text(text):
    lemmatizer = nltk.WordNetLemmatizer()
    return [lemmatizer.lemmatize(w) for w in text]

Assignment Objective: Create 3 models using pipelines¶

I'll be using the following sklearn guide to choose my classifier: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/tutorial/machine_learning_map/index.html

I'm using LogisticRegression for a general baseline.

I'm using LinearSVC according to the sklearn flowchart. I chose MultiNomialNB just to pick a model in the NaiveBayes family, in accordance with the linked flowchart.

I chose ComplementNB because the documentation specifically mentions that it's well suited for imbalanced data sets(#Assignment Objective)

An alternate method would be to gridsearch every classifier type model in the sklearn library, but in this case I'm going to defer to guide they've already provided.

I'm going to try a quick hyperparameter tune, since ComplementNB doesn't have a ton of complexity in that aspect. I won't be performning hyperparamenter tuning for the remaining models in the interest of time.

Thoughts
From Sklearn documentation:
"The F1 score can be interpreted as a weighted average of the precision and recall, where an F1 score reaches its best value at 1 and worst score at 0. The relative contribution of precision and recall to the F1 score are equal."

"weighted:
Calculate metrics for each label, and find their average weighted by support (the number of true instances for each label). This alters ‘macro’ to account for label imbalance; it can result in an F-score that is not between precision and recall."

Given this information, I belive that considering model performance by looking at weighted F1 score is a good choice. A Weighed F1 of 93% isn't horrible considering we've only taken basic steps to clean the data. We can clearly see the effects of the class imbalance, even thought we've taken steps to mitigate this when possible. The Model has high scores across the board in identifying our majority class(positive ratings), but shows less success when identifying the minority class(negative ratings). In addition the overall accuracy in identifying the correct sentiment was also pretty high, and ended up performing better than Vader.

We'll continue, and look at LinearSVC and MultinomialNB models since they were runners up in our first gridsearch for model comparison.

LinearSVC has consistently performed well in our past assignments for binary classification targets, so I'm not particularly suprised that it's performed well here too. One thing I found particularly interesting was it's dramatic improvent in recall score for 0, compared to the complement model. Given that we are interesting in identifying positive and negative sentiment, this model performs pretty well in identifying both. Because identifying both classes is equally import for sentiment analysis, This model appears to be perform best so far.
I think it's also worth nothing that this model has the highest macro F1 score, a metric that gives a well rounded view of the model performance in precision and recall.

Adding labels based on compound scores will help compare to the ML techniques.

According to Vader Documentation(https://github.com/cjhutto/vaderSentiment), the following is true:
positive sentiment: compound score >= 0.05
neutral sentiment: (compound score > -0.05) and (compound score < 0.05)
negative sentiment: compound score <= -0.05
The range of sentiment value is from -1.0 to 1.0, most negative to most positive.

Since we only labled positive and negative in our original df, I'm going to summarize this into compound > 0 as positive, and compound <= 0 as negative. This gives us access to better scoring methods against the sklearn models.

In [113]:
condition = [(df3['compound'] > 0 ), (df3['compound'] <=  0)]
values = [1, 0]

df3['vader_label'] = np.select(condition, values)

Thoughts:
Given how much less time it takes to get sentiment values out of vader(once I figured it out anyway), I'm surprised at it's scoring comparing to the sklearn ML classifiers.

In terms of real world application, I think Vader would be a great way to get a 'quick and dirty' idea of sentiment value in text, which could then be further refining in an sklearn classifier. Personally I'm really enjoing the sklearn package, so I would continue to use that. That being said, I'm aware that Vader has some great applications for use on social media, including emoji sentiment, so I think the strategic objective would dictate which approach to use.
